rows.text: Made thirty seven annual training cruises including six circumnavigations of the globe.
Built in England, is the largest ship afloat of its age in the Argentine Navy.

Launched in 1886. In 1941, during the armed conflict with Peru, BAE Abdon Calderón had a successful confrontation with Peruvian destroyer Admiral Villar, a ship that had vastly superior characteristics. Today it is a museum ship in Guayaquil, Ecuador.
A full rigged metal ship, built 1888.
Oldest surviving destroyer, escaped from Poland just before the German invasion began in 1939.
Combination cargo/passenger ship formerly used on the South American run.
She was used to service lighthouse buoys and lightships on the Australian coast.
Commissioned in 1942, opened as museum ship in 1973
Wooden 19th century whaler, only such U.S. ship remaining.
Only surviving clipper ship. Heavily damaged by fire in 2007, under restoration to reopen in 2012.
Commissioned 1 January 1974, opened as museum ship 8 May 2004.
The only surviving example of a large steam-powered torpedo boat. Built in 1907, she saw action during the Balkan Wars including a successful torpedo attack on a Turkish cruiser.
Completed 1968 - decommissioned 1992 - Museum ship in Milan, named after World War I Italian war hero Enrico Toti.
World's last surviving iron-hulled, four masted full-rigged ship and worlds only sail-driven oil tanker.
Only surviving example of a steam-powered sloop.
Former flagship of the Greek Navy. Last surviving armoured cruiser in the world.
Laid down in 1900 was the first submarine commissioned by the Royal Navy.
The only surviving Austro-Hungarian warship, launched in 1871.
Built 1510-12, she was one of the earliest purpose-built warships to serve in the Royal Navy. Sank in 1545 and raised in 1982.
The longest serving ship in the Thai Royal Navy, sixty years from 1937.
Decommissioned 2002; since September 2009 has been a museum ship in Genoa.
The submarine was decommissioned in 1998 and became a museum ship in 2004.
One of the longest-serving warships of the twentieth century. Most decorated battleship.
Now half destroyed by the earthquake and tsunami of February 27, 2010. There are proposals to recover to her previous condition of museum ship..
Was the last submarine built for the Royal Navy at historic Royal Dockyard in Chatham.
The only non-nuclear submarine of the Royal Navy to take part in the Falklands War.
Captured by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea in 1968.
One of the first torpedo craft, a class of warship that revolutionized naval warfare during the late nineteenth century.
Only surviving example of a heavy cruiser.
Currently the only museum ship of this type afloat in North America.
Launched in 1956, the Småland became one of the first destroyers to carry missiles as part of her armament.
The last U.S. Navy ship to sink an enemy ship in World War II..
The oldest British warship still afloat.
Only example of a wooden frigate 'in ordinary', or in a reserve fleet.
The world's only almost fully preserved 17th century warship. Sank on her maiden voyage in 1628 and salvaged in 1961.
Commissioned in 1973, it was one of the first submarines to serve in the Indian Navy.
Launched in 1860, Warrior was the first ocean-going iron hulled ship of its type.
One of the first hydrofoils in naval service.
